Hic ubi saepe] After he had broken the ice, Volteius was easily per· suaded to repeat his visits, till at last 110 became an established guest and a daily attendant at the 11011 man’s morning receptionS, till, on one occasion, he was invited to accompany Philippus to his country-seat in the Sabine country, during the ‘feriae Latinae.' This festival was of the highest an- tiquity. Its proper name was Latiar. The holidays lasted six days, during which all manner of festivities went on, and business was suspended. They were ‘feriae conceptivae,’ that is, they were annual, but not held always at the same season, which is what Horace means by calling them ‘indictae.' The magistrates appointed the time of their celebration.
